CAT AND THE AYATOLLAH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Khomeini does not represent me as a Muslim; he is the leader of the Shia 
minority, often self-righteous and misguided in their interpretation of Islamic 
law. 
</P>
<P>
His threat against Rushdie is wrong, and, I think, actually illegal, 
Islamically speaking. 
</P>
<P>
But Rushdie knew exactly what he was doing in savagely attacking truths all 
Muslims hold dear. My objection to Charles Champlin's article ("The Rushdie 
Affair -- a View From the Sidelines," Feb. 23) is this: Muslims have rules of 
civilized conduct, in which blasphemy is punishable; to defend the West as 
having defined the rules of civilized conduct for the entire world is 
hypocritical if one means to say that the West is superior in such matters. 
</P>
<P>
ABD AL-HAYY MOORE 
