<HEADLINE>
<P>
PROTESTANTISM IS SUFFERING 'MALAISE,' BAPTIST LEADER SAYS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
NEW YORK 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The chief executive of American Baptist Churches says mainline Protestantism is 
suffering from an "ecclesiastical malaise" that "touches almost every point in 
our denominational and ecumenical life." 
</P>
<P>
The Rev. Daniel Weis, in in a sermon at New York's Riverside Church, compared 
mainline Protestantism to the Prophet Ezekiel's vision of a "valley of dead, 
dry bones." 
</P>
<P>
However, he said "these bones can live" through "our transformation as a people 
revitalized by the spirit." 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Wire 
</P>
</TYPE>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
PROTESTANTS; RELIGION -- UNITED STATES; AMERICAN BAPTIST CHURCHES 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
</DOC>
